Hi Avinash,

Andrew has given an excellent analysis of your problem. It should be 
relatively easy to write a TestCase for the below class without having 
to worry about JNI, CORBA, or any XML-based configuration.

Working solely from the example you&#39;ve given below (and resisting the 
temptation to discuss refactoring the class to make it more testable 
_before_ writing a test case) I can see a whole host of TestCase 
candidates here, such as:

01. testMainWithServerConfigParametersCreatesReadyServer - by directly 
calling Server#main(String []) and using Assert#assertTrue on 
Server#isServerReady (or similar) we would be able to test if server 
configuration is successful. Such a test would also help by design by 
making us ask questions along the lines of &quot;What constitutes a ready 
server? Configured correctly? Started?&quot;

02. testGetInstanceAlwaysReturnsSameInstance - by using 
Assert#assertSame we can check that the Singleton design pattern is 
being enforced correctly. I&#39;m sorely tempted to suggest binning the 
Singleton pattern (is &quot;only one connection to the server at any one 
time&quot; an explicit intention?), but refactoring before we&#39;ve finished our 
TestCase would be a bit naughty.

03. testIsServerStarted/testIsServerStopped - these are 
self-explanatory, although they do bring us back to the question of 
ready vs. started again.

One strategy that would be very helpful here would be mocking - there 
are plenty of articles online related to mocking in JUnit, and some 
pretty good books as well.

Cheers,

Steve.

--
Stephen Smith, MEng (Wales).
http://www.stephen-smith.co.uk/

